{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "6682bd21ba0e94a3c4025ab4", "type": "singleCorrect", "level": 2, "category": null, "approximateTimeRequired": 90, "imageBaseUrl": null, "helperText": null, "source": "", "questionLabels": [], "question": {"text": "Which of the following statements are correct about <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cd</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Hg</mi></math> ?<br/>A. They exhibit high enthalpy of atomization as the d-subshell is full.<br/>B. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cd</mi></math> do not show variable oxidation state while <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Hg</mi></math> shows <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi>II</mi></math>.<br/>C. Compounds of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cd</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Hg</mi></math> are paramagnetic in nature.<br/>D. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Cd</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Hg</mi></math> are called soft metals.<br/>Choose the most appropriate from the options given below:", "image": null}, "options": [{"id": "8gja8", "text": "B, D only", "image": null, "isCorrect": true}, {"id": "nusw8", "text": "B, C only", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "SEivI", "text": "A, D only", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "ulZw8", "text": "C, D only", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}], "correctValue": null, "solution": {"text": "<p>(A) <math xmlns=\"